body:
Fewer can be just as effective as many, it just depends on which indices you're looking at. One popular investing strategy is a 3 fund portfolio: a US total market index fund + an international market fund + a bond fund gives excellent diversification. Ratios can be adjusted as you desire. [https://www.bogleheads.org/wiki/Three-fund\_portfolio](https://www.bogleheads.org/wiki/Three-fund_portfolio) It can be simplified into 2 funds if you use VT or VTWAX + a bond fund, or expanded by adding an international bond fund. It can be used as the core of your portfolio and added to if you wish, such as many people adding extra REITs. Edit: Internally, target date index funds either use or effectively use a 3 fund portfolio (Fidelity's is until closer to retirement where I think they also start adding in TIPS, Vanguard's is a 3 fund + international bonds then adds TIPS as well I believe, Schwab's is several of their ETFs that combined would come out to a 3 fund + REITs early on).

&amp;#x200B;

If this is outside an employer plan, you do not want to use any mutual funds from a company other than your brokerage (so don't use VTSAX at Fidelity or FTIHX at Vanguard) as you'll be hit with a commission (commission free doesn't apply to mutual funds from other companies). Using ETFs would be fine.

&amp;#x200B;

Using similar index funds from different companies would do nothing for diversification. So VTSAX (or VTI) + FSKAX is pointless  from a diversification standpoint. You also generally don't want to use a US total market fund + an S&amp;P 500 fund, as by weight roughly 80% of the total market fund would be the S&amp;P 500.

&amp;#x200B;

There are also multiple definitions of DCA, one of which is "investing regular amounts over time" (so investing money from each paycheck would count) and the other is specifically talking about only splitting up money you already have on hand (so investing as you earn wouldn't). Investing as you have the money available to do so is best 66% of the time, DCA as in the first definition would usually not be ideal.

Unless you have something like $100,000, I don't think you'd find a money market fund better than SPRXX. With money market funds, the 7-day yield already takes expense ratios into account.

&amp;#x200B;

Fidelity offers 4 index mutual funds (US total market style, international, essentially S&amp;P 500, and extended market) with no expense ratio at all. Their other index mutual funds are also the lowest I've seen anywhere and that's including ETFs (examples: a more complete US total market of FSKAX at 0.015%, international FTIHX at 0.06%, and bonds FXNAX at 0.025%).
